---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const description = "FTC consumer credit protections explained. Proof of indebtedness, debt collection litigation rules, and how the FTC enforces consumer rights in credit and debt collection.";
---

<Base title="FTC Consumer Credit Protections — CreditCookbook" description={description} posterTitle="FTC PROTECTIONS" posterLabel="// federal trade commission consumer rights">

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label" data-animate>// overview</span>
      <h2 data-animate style="margin-bottom: 24px;">What the FTC does for consumers.</h2>
      <p data-animate style="max-width: 64ch; margin-bottom: 32px; opacity: 0.8;">
        The Federal Trade Commission is the primary federal consumer protection agency in the United States. While the CFPB handles consumer complaints about financial products, the FTC enforces federal consumer protection laws including the FDCPA, FCRA, and rules against unfair and deceptive business practices.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="rule" />

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label" data-animate>// key areas</span>
      <h2 data-animate style="margin-bottom: 32px;">FTC enforcement areas affecting credit consumers.</h2>

      <div data-animate style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0;">

        <div style="border: 1px solid var(--line); padding: 32px; border-bottom: none;">
          <span class="section-label" style="color: var(--blue);">// area 01</span>
          <h3 style="margin-bottom: 12px;">Debt Collection Practices</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">The FTC enforces the FDCPA and monitors debt collection industry practices. Key enforcement priorities include:</p>
          <ul style="margin-left: 24px; line-height: 2; margin-bottom: 16px;">
            <li>Debt collectors filing lawsuits without proper documentation of indebtedness</li>
            <li>"Robo-signed" affidavits and false court filings</li>
            <li>Collection on debts that are past the statute of limitations</li>
            <li>Collection on debts that have been discharged in bankruptcy</li>
            <li>Harassment, false threats, and unauthorized third-party contacts</li>
          </ul>
          <p>The FTC has brought enforcement actions against major debt collectors for these practices, resulting in settlements and bans from the industry.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border: 1px solid var(--line); padding: 32px; border-top: none; border-bottom: none;">
          <span class="section-label" style="color: var(--blue);">// area 02</span>
          <h3 style="margin-bottom: 12px;">Credit Reporting Accuracy</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">The FTC enforces the FCRA alongside the CFPB. Key concerns include:</p>
          <ul style="margin-left: 24px; line-height: 2; margin-bottom: 16px;">
            <li>Furnishers providing inaccurate information to credit bureaus</li>
            <li>Bureaus failing to investigate disputes properly</li>
            <li>Mixed files (credit reports containing information from multiple consumers)</li>
            <li>Identity theft-related errors and failures to block fraudulent information</li>
          </ul>
          <p>The FTC conducts regular studies of credit report accuracy and publishes findings on errors affecting consumers.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border: 1px solid var(--line); padding: 32px; border-top: none; border-bottom: none;">
          <span class="section-label" style="color: var(--blue);">// area 03</span>
          <h3 style="margin-bottom: 12px;">Proof of Indebtedness</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">A critical FTC enforcement area: debt collectors must be able to prove you owe the debt they're collecting. The FTC has found that:</p>
          <ul style="margin-left: 24px; line-height: 2; margin-bottom: 16px;">
            <li>Many collection lawsuits are filed with minimal or no documentation</li>
            <li>Affidavits are often "robo-signed" — signed in bulk without review</li>
            <li>Debt buyers frequently lack the original account agreements</li>
            <li>Chain of custody for debt is often incomplete or missing</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;"><strong>What this means for you:</strong> When you request debt validation, you're exercising a right the FTC has identified as critical. Many collectors genuinely cannot produce the documentation required.</p>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;"><strong>Strategic response:</strong> In court, you can demand proof of standing — the collector must show they have the legal right to collect this specific debt from you. Many debt buyers purchased debts in bulk and have incomplete documentation.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border: 1px solid var(--line); padding: 32px; border-top: none;">
          <span class="section-label" style="color: var(--blue);">// area 04</span>
          <h3 style="margin-bottom: 12px;">Unfair and Deceptive Practices</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">Under Section 5 of the FTC Act, the FTC prohibits "unfair or deceptive acts or practices in or affecting commerce." This applies broadly to:</p>
          <ul style="margin-left: 24px; line-height: 2; margin-bottom: 16px;">
            <li>Credit repair companies that charge upfront fees (illegal under the FTC's Credit Repair Organizations Rule)</li>
            <li>Companies that falsely promise to remove accurate negative information</li>
            <li>Debt collectors who misrepresent the amount, legal status, or consequences of a debt</li>
            <li>Lenders who fail to disclose terms or engage in predatory lending</li>
          </ul>
          <p>If a credit repair company charges you upfront, they are violating federal law. The FTC's Credit Repair Organizations Rule (CROA) prohibits charging fees before services are fully performed.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="rule" />

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label" data-animate>// how to file</span>
      <h2 data-animate style="margin-bottom: 24px;">Filing a complaint with the FTC.</h2>
      <ol data-animate style="margin-left: 24px; line-height: 2.5; max-width: 64ch;">
        <li><strong>Go to ftccomplaintassistant.gov</strong> — the FTC's online complaint portal.</li>
        <li><strong>Select the category</strong> — "Debt Collection," "Credit Reporting," or "Credit Cards" depending on your issue.</li>
        <li><strong>Provide details</strong> — include the company name, dates, amounts, and a clear description of what happened.</li>
        <li><strong>Attach documentation</strong> — copies of letters, court filings, or credit reports (never originals).</li>
        <li><strong>Submit and keep your reference number</strong> — the FTC may follow up for more information.</li>
      </ol>
      <p data-animate style="max-width: 64ch; margin-top: 24px;">
        <strong>Important:</strong> The FTC does not resolve individual complaints — they use complaint data to identify patterns and bring enforcement actions. For individual resolution, also file with the CFPB at consumerfinance.gov/complaint, which handles individual consumer disputes with financial companies.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="rule" />

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label" data-animate>// enforcement actions</span>
      <h2 data-animate style="margin-bottom: 24px;">Notable FTC enforcement results.</h2>
      <table data-animate>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Action</th><th>Outcome</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Operation Collection Protection</td><td>Joint federal/state sweep — actions against collectors in 11 states</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Asset Acceptance settlement</td><td>$2.5M settlement — barred from collecting on debts without documentation</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Expert Credit Solutions ban</td><td>Owner banned from debt collection industry for fake attorney letters</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Midland Funding investigation</td><td>Scrutiny of robo-signed affidavits in debt collection lawsuits</td></tr>
          <tr><td>CROA enforcement</td><td>Numerous credit repair companies shut down for charging upfront fees</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p data-animate style="max-width: 64ch; margin-top: 24px; font-size: 14px; opacity: 0.7;">
        The FTC doesn't resolve individual cases — it builds enforcement cases from patterns. Your complaint matters because it contributes to the pattern that triggers action.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</Base>
